          "body": "The legal core (18:6-18) addresses prohibited degrees of sexual relation with remarkable comprehensiveness, covering blood relatives (mother, father's wife, sister, granddaughter, half-sister, father's sister, mother's sister), relatives by marriage (uncle's wife, daughter-in-law, brother's wife), and layered relationships (a woman and her daughter or granddaughter, two sisters simultaneously). The governing formula is 'uncover the nakedness' (galah + ervah) — an idiom for sexual intercourse that frames the prohibited act as a violation of the vulnerable person's proper covering. The principle is stated in 18:6: 'none of you shall approach any blood relative to uncover nakedness.' Every specific law that follows unpacks this principle. Modern anthropologists recognize incest prohibitions as near-universal, but Israel's rationale is theological, not merely sociological: to violate these boundaries is to defile the covenant family, dishonor the person wronged (cf. 'it is your father's nakedness,' 18:8), and ultimately dishonor the God who gave these statutes. Gordon Wenham (NICOT, Leviticus) notes that the phrase 'it is your father's nakedness' (18:8) implies that the wife shares in her husband's bodily integrity — the violation of the wife is simultaneously a violation of the husband."
