          "body": "Leviticus 18's most theologically distinctive contribution is its claim about the land (18:24-28). The chapter does not merely assert 'these things are wrong.' It asserts that these things defile the land, and that a defiled land vomits out its inhabitants. The verb translated 'spewed out' (qo, 18:25, 28) is the word for vomiting — visceral, bodily, involuntary rejection. The Canaanites are not simply being conquered for political or ethnic reasons; they are being expelled by a land that can no longer tolerate their moral defilement. This claim has deep roots in the Pentateuch's theology of creation. The land belongs to the Lord (Leviticus 25:23 — 'the land is Mine'); those who dwell in it are tenants. When tenants defile the owner's property, the owner evicts them. Israel's warning is explicit: the same mechanism applies to them regardless of covenant status. No ethnic privilege insulates Israel from the land's moral judgment. John Calvin, in his commentary on Leviticus, observed that this passage teaches that 'the earth itself, as it were, feels the pollution of sin, and refuses to bear those by whom it has been defiled.' Romans 8:19-22 extends this logic canonically: the whole creation groans under the weight of human sin, awaiting the redemption that will end its bondage to corruption."
