        "title": "A people between two empires — the call to a third way",
        "range": "18:1-5",
        "excerpt": "You shall not do what is done in the land of Egypt where you lived, nor are you to do what is done in the land of Canaan where I am bringing you; you shall not walk in their statutes.",
        "body": "The prologue of Leviticus 18 is one of the Old Testament's sharpest formulations of the covenant people's identity. Israel is not defined by what they are coming from (Egypt) or what they are entering (Canaan), but by who God is and what He commands. The double negation of verse 3 — not Egypt's practices, not Canaan's practices — creates the negative space inside which God's positive statutes fill. This is the same logic the New Testament employs when Paul commands the Roman church not to be 'conformed to this world' but to be 'transformed by the renewing of your mind' (Romans 12:2): the positive transformation is what fills the space left by the refusal to conform.\n\nThe historical pressure the prologue addresses is acute. Israel has spent four centuries in Egypt — long enough to absorb the ambient sexual norms of a culture whose religious system included fertility cults, divine-human sexual unions in temple contexts, and practices our text prohibits. Ezekiel 20:7-8 explicitly states that Israel had not abandoned the idols of Egypt before the exodus. The law does not assume that moral virtue accompanies geographical departure. Canaan, meanwhile, is not an empty moral space awaiting Israel's virtue; it is a land already morally saturated, as verses 24-27 will confirm. Israel cannot arrive and simply adapt; they must arrive having already internalized the alternative.\n\nVerse 5 is the prologue's theological summit: 'by which a man may live if he does them.' This is not merely pragmatic — obedience brings social stability, healthy families, reduced disease. It is covenantal: life (*chayah*) in its fullest sense is the reward of covenant obedience. The promise is real, not ironic. Paul's use of this verse in Romans 10:5 and Galatians 3:12 sets it in contrast with the principle of faith, but his point is not that the promise was false — it is that no one actually keeps the statutes perfectly enough to inherit life on that basis. The law reveals the standard of life-producing obedience; the gospel reveals the One who met it on behalf of those who could not.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chuqqah* (statutes, 18:3, 4, 5) — from a root meaning to engrave or inscribe. The word is used both for God's inscribed commands and for the nations' inscribed customs, creating a deliberate competition between two bodies of law. *Mishpat* (judgments, 18:4, 5) — judicial precedents that carry authority because they reflect the divine Judge's verdicts. *Chayah* (live, 18:5) — to live in the full sense; the Septuagint renders this *zēsetai*, the same root Paul uses in his citations."
