        "body": "The legal corpus opens with the broadest possible statement of the principle (18:6) before descending into specific cases. The governing idiom — 'uncover nakedness' (*galah ervah*) — frames sexual intercourse with a prohibited person as an act of violent exposure: removing the covering that protects the vulnerable party within a relationship of trust and proximity. The same verb *galah* is used in Nahum 3:5 for God's judgment of Nineveh ('I will lift your skirts over your face') and in Isaiah 47:3 for Babylon's humiliation. To uncover nakedness is always, in this idiom, an act of violation.\n\nThe structure of the incest prohibitions moves through three relational circles. The innermost circle (18:7-11) covers the nuclear family and step-relations — mother, father's wife, sister (full and half), granddaughter, step-sister. The middle circle (18:12-14) covers extended blood relations — father's sister, mother's sister, father's brother's wife (aunt). The outer circle (18:15-18) covers relations by marriage — daughter-in-law, brother's wife, a wife's sister taken simultaneously. The comprehensiveness is intentional: the law does not leave ambiguities that the inventive can exploit.\n\nThe rationale supplied in several cases is significant. 'It is your father's nakedness' (18:8, 16) — the wife shares in her husband's bodily integrity; to violate her is to violate him. 'For their nakedness is yours' (18:10) — the granddaughter's vulnerability is an extension of the grandfather's own honor; incest with her is a form of self-violation. 'It is lewdness' (*zimmah*, 18:17) — the most explicit evaluative term in the incest section, reserved for the most layered violation (a woman and her daughter or granddaughter). These rationales show that the prohibitions are not arbitrary but are rooted in a theology of relational integrity: each person within the family network has a dignity and a proper covering that incest tears away.\n\nGordon Wenham (NICOT) and John Hartley (WBC) both note that Leviticus 18's incest laws are significantly broader than those of the surrounding cultures' law codes (Hammurabi, Hittite laws), which prohibited far fewer degrees of relation. The breadth of Israel's laws reflects not cultural conservatism but theological conviction: the family is a covenant institution whose boundaries are sacred because they image the relational faithfulness of the covenant God.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ervah* (nakedness) appears as both noun and verb-object throughout 18:6-19, sometimes personified: 'her nakedness' or 'his nakedness' refers to the sexual vulnerability of the prohibited person. *Sheer* (close relative, 18:6, 12, 13) — literally 'flesh,' emphasizing that the prohibition is rooted in the shared bodily reality of family belonging. *Zimmah* (18:17) — from a root meaning to plan or scheme; this is not impulsive sin but deliberate wickedness."
